WEBVTT

00:00:01.760 --> 00:00:08.800
<v Speaker 1>So now we have we really do have the panorama of all times and moods in Spanish.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:10.640
<v Speaker 1>So now that's everything.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:17.360
<v Speaker 1>That's every tense including both the idea of time and the idea of mood.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:24.960
<v Speaker 1>We've learnt how to construct them all and we should really listen actively to refresh.

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:30.900
<v Speaker 1>Any knowledge that we might need to refresh through our exposure to Spanish.

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:31.300
<v Speaker 1>No?

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:33.540
<v Speaker 1>Analyzing always what we hear.

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:37.780
<v Speaker 1>And if you're listening to a song or a movie, maybe you just hear the endings

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:43.540
<v Speaker 1>of the verbs at the beginning, but if you can identify what that ending means, that's the important bit.

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:47.220
<v Speaker 1>In the same way this course has been focused

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:56.260
<v Speaker 1>equally on the process that we go through in building our structures in Spanish as it has been focused on content.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:01:06.860
<v Speaker 1>So half of the point of this course has been content, has been teaching you Spanish, and the other half has been how to manage Spanish

00:01:07.020 --> 00:01:15.100
<v Speaker 1>How to manage these elements that we've learned, how to think about this information and how to relate to information generally in a new way.

00:01:15.100 --> 00:01:19.340
<v Speaker 1>How to find things that you think you might have forgotten

00:01:19.340 --> 00:01:30.700
<v Speaker 1>We've also looked now and then at some irregularities in Spanish, verbs or other words that don't follow the rules that we learnt.

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:35.500
<v Speaker 1>Now, the older the language, the more irregularities it tends to have.

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:42.300
<v Speaker 1>Spanish, effectively being modern Latin, is quite prone to irregularities

00:01:42.439 --> 00:01:47.560
<v Speaker 1>But the irregularities can be made sense of within themselves.

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:49.960
<v Speaker 1>You can group together irregularities.

00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:55.560
<v Speaker 1>So whilst throughout the course we were looking at the odd irregularity as it popped up

00:01:55.460 --> 00:02:01.460
<v Speaker 1>Now at the end of the course we are going to tidy up the irregular verbs.

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:04.020
<v Speaker 1>So there are a group of verbs.

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:06.140
<v Speaker 1>Which we can call the got verbs.

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:12.060
<v Speaker 1>These are the verbs that use go instead of o for the I form.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:14.780
<v Speaker 1>For example, how do you say to have?

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:18.380
<v Speaker 1>To have for possession?

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:19.079
<v Speaker 2>Tener.

00:02:19.079 --> 00:02:21.720
<v Speaker 1>Tener and I have?

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:22.599
<v Speaker 2>Tengo.

00:02:22.599 --> 00:02:23.480
<v Speaker 1>Tengo.

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:27.480
<v Speaker 1>So this go pops up for the I version, but only for the I version.

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:30.519
<v Speaker 1>How do you say he has or she has, you fool have

00:02:31.540 --> 00:02:40.659
<v Speaker 1>Tiene and you informal tienes and they tienen and we

00:02:42.200 --> 00:02:43.159
